Context & objectives

Integration of the RMI + Pameseb AWS networks

Assessing the agreement level between the 2 types of AWS

  • previous work by Geoff Jenkins described a comparison method based on regression model correlation study.
  • as demonstrated by Giavarina, correlation studies is not appropriate to study the differences.
  • The alternative Bland-Altman analysis proposed by the authors is used in this study.

Investigating the temperature difference

Bland-Altman analysis

We can use a Bland Altman analysis to measure the agreement level between the 2 stations.

It consists to take observations pair by pair, and plot their means vs.Â their differences.

In our case we choose to plot IRM - Pameseb.

Vizualizing Bland-Altman analyis

What the Bland-Altman plot tells us ?

  • For most individuals, measurements made by 2 stations are more likely to be far apart between [-0.78 - 0.69] Â°C.

  • 0 is not in the 95% CI of the mean difference [-0.77 - -0.037 ] ==> It exists a systematic positif bias of -0.043

  • Considering the limits of agreement CI [-0.78 and 0.69], we can tell that we are 95 % certain that the methods do not disagree (if maximum allowed difference is 1Â°C)

  • The scatter presents a trend going from positive bias to negative bias ==> proportional bias. The methods do not agree equally through the range of measurements.

  • The RMI - Pameseb temperature differences are negatively correlated with the temperature means.

Plausible hypothesis to investigate

The 2 stations are actually different in their design. While the RMI is equipped with a Stevenson radiation screeen mechanically ventiled, __Pameseb is equipped with a custom screen without mechanical ventilation

We can assume that it exists :

  1. an overheating of the Pameseb shelter compared to RMI during periods of High irradiance and low wind due to the lack of ventilation system at Pameseb that may significantly increase the measured temperature.

  2. an overcooling of the RMI shelter compared to Pameseb during periods of Low irradiance + stratified air situation due to the fact that the ventilation pumps air located 50 cm below the temperature sensor.

Visualising the 2 designs

Questioning the potential effect of the ventilation

Low irradiance and high wind BA Plot

What the Low irradiance and high wind BA plot tells us ?

  • It exists a systematic bias of 0.1175583

  • The limits of agreement are -0.271789 and 0.5069055 Â°C. These lines tell us how far apart measurements by 2 methods were more likely to be for most individuals.

  • Considering the limits of agreement CI (-0.271789 and 0.5069055 ), we can tell that we are 95 % certain that the methods do not disagree (if maximum allowed difference is 1Â°C)

  • The differences are still present but are clearly less important. Some discrepancies due to outliers

  • Even with no irradiance, the rising trend is still present. How can this be ? According to RMI, the ventilation system pumps up air 50 cm below the sensor. While the atmosphere is stratified, the RMI shelter might be ventiled with colder air than the one it is supposed to measureâ¦

  • ==> So the rising trend might also be due to an artifical âover-coolingâ rather than the combined effect of high irradiance + low wind only
